                <script type="text/javascript"
                  src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
                </script></div>
                <span id="Body"><p>I see that <a href="http://radio.weblogs.com/0108971/2003/06/30.html#a206">Clemens Vasters</a> has also soured on <span class="caps">AOP. </span>The primary weakness of the <span class="caps">AOP</span> approach is due to the difficulty of writing stateful aspects that are composable. In his piece, Clemens calls stateful aspects "opaque aspects" and stateless aspects "passive aspects". While he describes a bunch of nasty technical issues that got in the way of having a clean implementation, the composability problem will nevertheless limit the utility of <span class="caps">AOP.</span></p>



<p>The only point that I disagree with in his article is how he characterizes AspectJ pointcuts as equivalent to the use of attributes in the <span class="caps">CLR. </span>AspectJ pointcuts are an example of a "push" mechanism for weaving aspects, whereas attributes are an example of a "pull" mechanism for weaving aspects. In AspectJ, you don't need to touch the source code to weave an aspect into a particular join point, whereas with attributes you do need to touch the source code to achieve the same effect.</p>
</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ByLine">
                By
                <span id="Author" class="Author">John</span>
